<!-- /wp:html -->
<!-- wp:heading {"level":1,"style":{"typography":{"fontSize":"clamp(32px,4vw,48px)"}}} -->
<h1 class="wp-block-heading" style="font-size:clamp(32px,4vw,48px)">Local SEO in Turin: getting found between industry and export</h1>
<!-- /wp:heading -->
<!-- wp:html -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large" style="margin:8px 0 8px"><img src="/wp-content/themes/remarka-studio/assets/img/blog/seo-torino-cover.svg" alt="Local SEO in Turin: the map with the first three results for whoever is looking for a supplier or a service in the manufacturing city" width="1200" height="630" loading="lazy" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;border:1px solid var(--sr-bordo)"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:html -->
</section>
<!-- /wp:group -->
<!-- wp:group {"tagName":"section","className":"sr-section","layout":{"type":"constrained","contentSize":"1440px"}} -->
<section class="wp-block-group is-layout-constrained sr-section"><!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch">A machine shop in Barriera di Milano, a components supplier in Moncalieri, a design studio in Vanchiglia: in Turin serious product is never in short supply, and the customer is often a technical buyer looking for a local supplier from their phone, between one shift and the next. Local SEO in Turin is what decides whether, when someone searches «machining Turin» or «web agency Turin», you show up or the competitor two blocks away does. It’s not a contest of buzzwords: it’s work made of precise signals. Let’s see how it works in a city of manufacturing and export, and where to start.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:heading {"style":{"typography":{"fontSize":"clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)"}}} -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading" style="font-size:clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)">Why in Turin local SEO speaks to manufacturing<span class="sr-accent-dot">.</span></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">Turin doesn’t live on brochures: it lives on manufacturing, automotive, aerospace and design. The area has over 221,000 businesses with more than 800,000 employees, one of the densest industrial fabrics in Italy (Turin Chamber of Commerce and Unione Industriali). In the automotive components supply chain alone, of which Turin is the historic heart, more than 2,000 businesses operate. In a context like this, the customer is almost never a tourist’s impulse: it’s a purchasing manager comparing suppliers, who judges you also by how they find you and how fast your site opens.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">This changes the meaning of local SEO in Turin. The «near me» search here matters for the restaurant and the shop, but the richer game is another: being found, locally and beyond, for the specific machining, the component, the technical service. Showing up for «supplier Turin» in a vague sense isn’t enough; you need to be relevant to the precise search of whoever is looking for exactly what you do, when they’re looking for it.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:heading {"style":{"typography":{"fontSize":"clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)"}}} -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading" style="font-size:clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)">The local pack and Google’s three factors<span class="sr-accent-dot">.</span></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">In Turin too the heart of local search is the «local pack»: the block with the map and three businesses that Google shows at the top of results with local intent. On mobile it’s the first thing the eye meets, and being in those three boxes is worth more than ten organic positions. For a workshop or a studio, it’s the difference between receiving the enquiry and staying invisible.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">Google explains how it chooses who to show: in its official guide to local ranking it points to three factors — relevance, distance and prominence. Relevance depends on how well your profile matches the search; distance on where you are relative to whoever is searching; prominence on how well known you are, reviews included. They’re three concrete levers, and for a Turin company relevance — the right category, services well described — is often the most neglected and most profitable one.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:html -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large" style="margin:36px 0 8px"><img src="/wp-content/themes/remarka-studio/assets/img/blog/seo-torino-schema.svg" alt="The three factors of local SEO in Turin according to Google: relevance, distance and prominence, which decide the local pack" width="1200" height="500" loading="lazy" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;border:1px solid var(--sr-bordo)"/><figcaption class="sr-mono" style="margin-top:12px;font-size:12.5px;letter-spacing:0.04em;color:var(--sr-grigio);max-width:75ch">The three factors with which Google decides the local pack: relevance (how well the profile matches the search), distance (how close you are to whoever is searching) and prominence (how well known you are). For Turin’s industry, relevance — category and services well described — is often the most neglected lever. Source: Google, official guide to local ranking.</figcaption></figure>
<!-- /wp:html -->
<!-- wp:heading {"style":{"typography":{"fontSize":"clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)"}}} -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading" style="font-size:clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)">The Google profile, curated like a catalogue<span class="sr-accent-dot">.</span></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">The engine of local SEO is the Google profile (Google Business Profile): it appears on the map with name, hours, photos, phone and reviews, and for many searches the customer decides looking only at that. For a technical company it’s worth treating it the way you treat a catalogue: precise category, listed services, real photos of the workshop or the products, correct hours. A vague or abandoned profile tells the buyer exactly what you don’t want it to say.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">Reviews weigh on trust and ranking together: according to BrightLocal’s annual survey, almost everyone reads them before choosing. In B2B too they count more than you’d think — a buyer evaluating a new supplier looks at them. Asking a satisfied client for one, after a job well done, is among the zero-cost moves with the highest return.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:html -->
<p class="sr-card-link" style="margin-top:14px"><a href="https://support.google.com/business/answer/7091" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Google — guide to local ranking →</a></p><p class="sr-card-link" style="margin-top:14px"><a href="/en/blog/google-business-profile-guide/">Read also: Google Business Profile, the storefront nobody tends →</a></p>
<!-- /wp:html -->
<!-- wp:heading {"style":{"typography":{"fontSize":"clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)"}}} -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading" style="font-size:clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)">The website: structured data, speed and a findable catalogue<span class="sr-accent-dot">.</span></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">In Turin the site isn’t a whim, it’s a piece of engineering — and for local SEO it counts twice. First: the LocalBusiness structured data from schema.org tells Google, explicitly, where you are and what you do, with name, address and phone consistent everywhere. Second: speed. A technical catalogue that opens in six seconds on the phone, while the buyer in Stuttgart waits less than one, is lost traffic; and slowness weighs on ranking too.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">Then there’s local and international content together. Many Turin companies sell across half of Europe: «local» local SEO coexists with well-done international SEO, versions in other languages translated by native speakers and with correct hreflang. Before adding pages, though, it’s worth measuring the signals your site already sends: structure, structured data, real speed.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:html -->
<p class="sr-card-link" style="margin-top:14px"><a href="/en/services/technical-seo/">Structured data and technical SEO in every site →</a></p><p class="sr-card-link" style="margin-top:14px"><a href="/en/tools/eeat-signals/">Measure your home page’s E-E-A-T signals and structured data for free →</a></p><p class="sr-card-link" style="margin-top:14px"><a href="https://developers.google.com/search/docs/appearance/structured-data/intro-structured-data" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Google — structured data and LocalBusiness →</a></p>
<!-- /wp:html -->
<!-- wp:heading {"style":{"typography":{"fontSize":"clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)"}}} -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading" style="font-size:clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)">Where to start, in Turin and toward foreign markets<span class="sr-accent-dot">.</span></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">The order is always the same: first the Google profile (complete, verified, with genuine reviews), then the site (structured data, speed, content), and finally prominence. For a company that exports, one level is added: making yourself findable also by whoever searches for you from abroad, with a site ready for the markets you sell in. Local SEO and export SEO aren’t in conflict — they’re the same technical work, extended to the right languages.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">This work we do where the clients are: in Turin we have a real office and the first meeting — at your company or ours — is free. We analyse the current profile and site, we look at the catalogue’s speed on mobile, and we tell you what’s missing in black and white. Then we work to get you found, in the city and in the markets that interest you.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:html -->
